const bostonHead = "Boston, MA"
const abstractText = "As next-generation sequencing (NGS) applications expand toward large-scale screening, existing library preparation workflows face significant scalability challenges. Conventional workflows rely on manual, plate-based processing that becomes labor-intensive and error-prone at scale. Although automation has been adopted, most high-throughput platforms simply scale plate-based reactions without miniaturization, leading to excessive reagent consumption. To address these challenges, we developed an automated nanoliter dispensing and imaging platform, the Shasta® Single Cell System, to enable either high-throughput single-cell or bulk library preparations at the nanoliter scale. The Shasta system utilizes positive-displacement nanosyringes that can reliably mix and multi-dispense cells and reagents from 25 to 100 nl. Samples, reagents, and barcodes are dispensed into a 5,184-nanowell chip for downstream reactions. For single-cell library preparation, we miniaturized the PicoPLEX® whole-genome-amplification (WGA) workflow 100-fold, from 30 µl to 300 nl per cell. We first dispensed a fluorescent-labeled cell suspension into the nanowell chip and scanned. Within 2.5 min, a convolutional neural network (CNN) image analysis model detected all the single cells. Each nanowell containing a single cell then underwent the WGA workflow through stacked 50 nl reagent dispenses for DNA extraction, pre-amplification, amplification PCR, and P5/P7 indexing. Using a dual-chip configuration, over 4,000 single-cell WGA libraries were generated in a single run. Genome coverage uniformity and mapping rates were comparable to plate-based methods, which are limited to only 96 or 384 libraries per run. To evaluate the copy number variation (CNV) detection sensitivity, two cell lines with well-characterized CNVs were processed: GM22601 (~25 Mb deletion on chromosome 4) and GM05067 (~45 Mb gain on chromosome 9). These segmental aneuploidies were reliably detected in >90% of cells at a read depth as low as ~100,000 reads per cell. For bulk library preparation, the Shasta system can process up to 384 samples with 12 replicates each. As a proof-of-principle, we dispensed 96 RNA samples with a wide concentration range of 1–50 ng per microliter. 35 nl of RNA was dispensed into each nanowell, followed by stacked reagent dispenses for reverse transcription, amplification PCR, tagmentation, and P5/P7 indexing. The total reaction volume of 285 nl per replicate is a ~300-fold reduction from standard plate-based mRNA-seq kits. With a shallow sequencing depth of ~120,000 reads per sample, we detected an average of ~7,000 genes, demonstrating comparable gene detection sensitivity with volume miniaturization. By combining miniaturization with automated dispensing and imaging, we achieved nanoliter-scale library preparation while maintaining the sensitivity of CNV detection for single-cell WGA and gene detection for bulk RNA-seq. The flexible, nanoliter-scale dispensing volume range of the Shasta system is expected to support future adaptation of a broad range of high-throughput NGS chemistries."

const posterTitle1 = "Presented a poster at SLAS 2026. Four full days of socialising and learning about the current technological landscape was both exhausting and rejuvenating, and I am very much looking forward to the next conference!"
const posterTitle2 = "Poster title: \"Automated single-cell and bulk NGS library preparation at the nanoliter scale maintains sensitivity while reducing reagent usage\" "
